sentences: Paul Mars Black (born Paul Marmorstein; March 17, 1959) is an American singer and drummer.
In the 1970s, his high school rock band was called Your Mother.
In 1978 he was a percussion major at San Jose State University.
Black moved to Los Angeles in May 1980 still using his given name Paul Martin Marmorstein.
In 1981 Paul joined The Mau-Mau's, a Los Angeles-based punk band which was fronted by Rick Wilder of The Berlin Brats.
In 1984 Paul Mars Joined The Joneses and recorded the drums for Keeping Up With The Joneses.

The name was switched to L.A. Guns because the owner of the name, Raz Cue, offered to back the band if this line up would re-use L.A. Guns, a name which had been abandoned over a year prior by a former band of Guns's (Guns N' Roses).
From 1985 to March 1987 Paul Black wrote and co-wrote a number of songs, which led L.A. Guns to a record deal with Polygram Records.
Black retired in 1993 and seldom played shows.
In 2000 Black wrote and recorded an album with Jo Almeida of Dogs D'Amour called Jo & Paul's Sonic Boom, Sun Down And Yellow Moon.

From 2006 to 2008, he was the lead singer of Tracii Guns's L.A. Guns, a spinoff band that existed at the same time as Phil Lewis' L.A. Guns.
